### Ear-EEG / in-ear EEG specifically
| Study             | Year | N subj | Device        | Kappa     | Notes |
|-------------------|------|--------|---------------|-----------|-------|
| Mikkelsen et al.  | 2019 | ~20    | Custom dry    | 0.73-0.74 | Single-ear, subject-independent |
| Tabar et al.      | 2023 | ~15    | Dry earpiece  | 0.70      | Subject-independent |
| L-SeqSleepNet     | 2023 | ~15    | Ear-EEG DB    | 0.829     | In-distribution, homogeneous DB |
| Scalp-to-ear xfer | 2024 | 13     | In-ear        | 0.589-0.639| Fine-tuned YASA, older adults |

## Positioning
1. At human inter-rater ceiling (0.754 vs 0.76) on a genuinely hard 17-dataset OOD benchmark.
2. Cross-dataset generalization: competitive with best published OOD results (0.66-0.78),
   despite being single-channel vs multi-channel for Stephansen/U-Sleep.
3. Ear-EEG specifically: above any published subject-independent ear-EEG result (0.70-0.74),
   and approaching the best in-distribution ear-EEG result (L-SeqSleepNet 0.829, single DB).
4. Gap vs in-distribution SOTA (0.838): ~0.08 kappa -- but in-dist vs OOD is not apples-to-apples.
   Stephansen loses 0.09-0.12 kappa going OOD; our model is designed to not have in-dist numbers.
5. U-Sleep (0.819 OOD) uses 7x more data and multi-channel EEG+EOG -- single-channel constraint
   is meaningful (wearable target), not just a handicap.

## Critical caveat
Published in-distribution numbers (0.82-0.84) rarely generalize: Stephansen drops to 0.66-0.69 OOD.
Our honest OOD benchmark (335 subjects, 17 datasets, no data seen during training) is the correct
comparison for a real-world deployment target. SOMNUS (0.89) is the only multi-dataset multi-channel
model with a comparable honest evaluation, but uses 12x more data and multi-channel setup.

2026-02-24: v11 architecture -- signed theta + slowwave + sawtooth decoders
================================================================

## Decoder changes (all now default)
Three changes baked into train_encoder.py defaults:
1. **theta rectify False**: theta decoder target changed from envelope (abs) to signed waveform.
   Preserves sawtooth wave asymmetry in REM theta band (4-8 Hz). Was rectify=True.
2. **slowwave decoder**: new BranchDecoder(128) on large CNN (feat_l), 0.5-1 Hz signed.
   Targets slow oscillation morphology (narrower than delta decoder's 0.5-4 Hz).
3. **sawtooth decoder**: new BranchDecoder(128) on medium CNN (feat_m), 2-6 Hz signed.
   Targets REM sawtooth wave morphology (spans delta/theta boundary).

Rationale: N3/REM both confused with N2 (11-24% confusion). N3-N2 is a slow-wave counting
vs power problem; sawtooth waves (2-6 Hz, REM-specific) are not captured by theta envelope.
Signed targets preserve waveform asymmetry that distinguishes these stages.

## Codebase cleanup
- Deleted all checkpoint/log/plot artifacts: abl_*, compile_bench, v10
- Updated analyze_residuals.py: fixed theta rectify=True bug, added slowwave/sawtooth tracking
- Updated CLAUDE.md: training command simplified (all flags now default), decoder table updated

## Current state
- Architecture: 5-branch encoder (640d) + 7 recon decoders (training-only)
- New decoders add 130K params (training-only, discarded after encoder training)
- Status: awaiting full v11 training run (50 epochs, ~2.5h with torch.compile)

